Slack Reviews & Product Details















Slack is your single workspace that connects you with the people and tools you work with everyday, no matter where you are or what you do. With Slack you get real-time messaging through calls and chat, a searchable record of all your files and conversations, and integrations with a growing number of handy bots and apps. Now everyone can finally be on the same page and get their work done. Slack: It’s where work happens.

G2 reviews are authentic and verified.
Here's how.
We strive to keep our reviews authentic.
G2 reviews are an important part of the buying process, and we understand the value they provide to  both our customers and buyers. To ensure the value is retained, it's important to make certain that  reviews are authentic and trustworthy, which is why G2 requires verified methods to write a review and  validates the reviewer's identity before approving. G2 validates the reviewers identity with our  moderation process that prevents inauthentic reviews, and we strive to collect reviews in a responsible and ethical manner.

"Smooth UX with Seamless Integrations"






What do you like best about Slack?
I use Slack for communicating with my colleagues through chats and calls. It's really easy to navigate, and I find the calls seamless. The user interface and user experience are great; it's easy on the eyes. I appreciate that files are located under a single tab, and the ability to search text under specific channels is a big plus. Slack also supports a good number of external plugins, like Outlook, which pings and reminds me of any upcoming meetings. The user experience feels very smooth, and it's easy to navigate, search, and access messages through the applications. Review collected by and hosted on G2.com.
What do you dislike about Slack?
I sometimes don’t get notifications even though not on mute. They also sometimes get delayed, although very rarely. Occasional connection issues. Review collected by and hosted on G2.com.
What problems is Slack solving and how is that benefiting you?
Slack is easy to navigate, offers seamless calls, and has a user-friendly UI. Files are under a single tab, text search is efficient in channels, and external plugins like Outlook improve meeting reminders. Review collected by and hosted on G2.com.

"Essential for Seamless Remote Team Communication"






What do you like best about Slack?
Slack helps our fully-remote team communicate across daily 3 time zones without missing a beat. We can have a dozen different conversations on different topics and (usually) keep up with them all across the Slack platform. There are options for direct messages and for team conversations. It integrates with Google Drive to show previews right in the channel. It helps us link to our larger organization as well. It's all searchable, so if we can't remember where something is, it's not too hard to find. We use it constantly and it's the backbone of our project. I've never had a problem requiring help from Customer Support; it's easy to use. Review collected by and hosted on G2.com.
What do you dislike about Slack?
We rely on it so much that sometimes it gets a little unwieldy. A team member who happens to miss a conversation logs on later only to find 145 replies and nobody wants to read that thread. Review collected by and hosted on G2.com.
What problems is Slack solving and how is that benefiting you?
My team works in three different time zones and we all have different specialities and areas of expertise. Slack makes it easy to actually communicate with each other. Email and phone would be insufficient; Slack incorporates the links, documents, and history we need and combines it all in one space. Review collected by and hosted on G2.com.

"Drives Fast Collaboration and Seamless Integrations"






What do you like best about Slack?
I like Slack because it drives real time cross team coordination and faster decisions, keeping work visible in channels where we already collaborate. I use it to run discovery threads, share config files, and get quick feedback from partners in DS and IDM without meetings. Its integrations bring signals to me, like Qualtrics updates in channel and orchestration alerts tied to Sidekick workflows, so I do not have to chase status across tools. It is also a first class interface for tools like MOOSE, letting me share sessions and collect feedback directly in chat to reduce context switching. Onboarding and identity are simple, so getting set up or sharing my member ID for access is quick when teammates need to add me to apps or channels. Review collected by and hosted on G2.com.
What do you dislike about Slack?
Here is what I dislike about Slack in my day to day work. It makes it easy for work to fragment across DMs and channels, so decisions and context get buried and search often does not surface the one message I need. Channel sprawl and notification noise make it hard to keep up without muting something important. Threads are inconsistent and easy to break, which scatters conversations and leaves me reconstructing context later. Files shared in chat drift into multiple versions and are hard to rediscover, so I still need a separate source of truth in Confluence or Jira. Integrations are valuable, but they can create alert fatigue and make it harder to distinguish signal from noise. Access and app management can also be clunky at times, like when I need to pass around member IDs or wait on approvals to add bots. In short, Slack is great for speed, but it is not great for permanence, structure, or findability. Review collected by and hosted on G2.com.
What problems is Slack solving and how is that benefiting you?
Slack solves slow, siloed communication and meeting overload by giving me real time, asynchronous collaboration in channels where the work already lives, so I can move conversations forward without waiting on calendars. I benefit by getting rapid feedback in discovery threads and config reviews with DS and IDM, sharing files and decisions in one place instead of hopping between tools or scheduling standups. Its integrations route signals to me, like Qualtrics updates and workflow alerts tied to Sidekick orchestration, which means I do not have to chase status across systems. It is also a first class interface for internally developed tools, so I can share sessions and collect feedback directly in chat, reducing context switching and speeding iteration. Onboarding and identity are straightforward, with clear workspace steps and a copyable member ID, which makes it easy for teammates to add me to apps and channels when needed. Review collected by and hosted on G2.com.
